{{Italic title}}'''''Idées républicaines''''' (''Republican ideas'') is a political pamphlet by the French philosopher and author [[Voltaire]].<ref name="Gay_content">{{cite book|last1=Gay|first1=Peter|title=Voltaire's Politics: The Poet as Realist|date=1959|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=New Jersey|pages=214–219}}</ref> It was published anonymously and undated, but is thought to have been written in late 1765.<ref name="Gay_date">{{cite book|last1=Gay|first1=Peter|title=Voltaire's Politics: The Poet as Realist|date=1959|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=New Jersey|chapter=Appendix II}}</ref> It defends free thought and free expression in general, and also contains Voltaire's thoughts on the ongoing campaign for democracy in [[Geneva]], where he supported greater power for the citizens.<ref name="Aldridge">{{cite book|last1=Aldridge|first1=A. Owen|title=Voltaire and the Century of Light|date=1975|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=New Jersey|page=335}}</ref>
== Content == The pamphlet includes critical commentary on [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]]'s ''[[The Social Contract]]'' and [[Montesquieu]]'s ''[[The Spirit of the Laws]]''.<ref name="davidson"/>
It also defends the natural right to [[free expression]]. ''The Social Contract'' had been burned at Geneva. Voltaire writes, "The operation of burning it was perhaps as odious as that of writing it. [...] If the book was dangerous, it should have been refuted. To burn a book of argument is to say: 'We do not have enough wit to reply to it.'"<ref name="Gay_content"/><ref name="davidson"/> He comments that England, despite being a monarchy, has a more enlightened population than other countries because the right to publish is protected by law.<ref name="davidson">{{cite book|last1=Davidson|first1=Ian|title=Voltaire in Exile|date=2004|publisher=Atlantic books|isbn=1843540878|pages=186–187}}</ref>
Voltaire writes that a perfect government is impossible, but that a [[republic]] is the closest to achieving natural equality.<ref name="davidson"/>
There are many textual similarities between ''Idées républicaines'' and Voltaire's private memorandum on the struggle in Geneva, ''Propositions à examiner pour apaiser les division de Genève''.<ref name="Gay_date"/>
