'''The Prehistoric Society''' is an international [[learned society]] devoted to the study of the human past from the earliest times until the emergence of [[recorded history|written history]].
Now based at [[University College London]] in the United Kingdom, it was founded by [[V. Gordon Childe]], [[Stuart Piggott]] and [[Grahame Clark]] in 1935<ref>{{cite book |title=A "splendid idiosyncrasy": prehistory at Cambridge 1915-50 |last=Smith |first=Pamela Jane |page=59 |year=2009 |publisher=[[Archaeopress]] |isbn=978-1-4073-0430-4 }}</ref> but also traces its founding to the earlier '''Prehistoric Society of East Anglia'''<ref>{{cite book |title=Prehistory at Cambridge and beyond |authorlink=Grahame Clark |last=Clark |first=Grahame |page=35 |year=1989 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0-521-35031-0 }}</ref> which began in 1908.<ref name="About">{{cite web | url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prehistoric/title.html | title=About | publisher=[[University College London]] / The Prehistoric Society | accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> The society is a [[Charitable organization|registered charity]] under English law.<ref>{{EW charity|1000567|THE PREHISTORIC SOCIETY}}</ref>
Membership is by subscription and includes the annual journal, '''''Proceedings of the Prehistoric Society''''' {{ISSN|0079-497X}} (Print), {{ISSN|2050-2729}} (Online),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/proceedings-of-the-prehistoric-society | title=Proceedings of the Prehistoric Society | publisher=Cambridge Core | accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> which continues ''Proceedings of the Prehistoric Society of East Anglia'' (1911-1934) {{ISSN|0958-8418}} (Print),<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/proceedings-of-the-prehistoric-society/past-title/proceedings-of-the-prehistoric-society-of-east-anglia/information/404998E0E254C9D61CB1B2D9EE5A0710 | title=Proceedings of the Prehistoric Society of East Anglia | publisher=Proceedings of the Prehistoric Society, [[Cambridge Core]] | accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> and bulletins from the newsletter, ''PAST'', which is published in April, July and November. It also organises regular conferences, lectures and other events and makes grants for [[archaeology|archaeological]] research.
