'''Toby Christopher Barnard''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|commas=on|FBA|size=100%}} is emeritus fellow in history at [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]], University of Oxford. He joined the college in 1976 and retired in 2012.<ref>"Toby Barnard retires" in ''The Hertford College Magazine'', No. 92, 2012, pp. 29-31.</ref> He was formerly lecturer in history at [[Royal Holloway]] (1970-1976). Barnard is a specialist in the political, social and cultural histories of Ireland and England, c. 1600-1800.<ref>[http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/elections/index.cfm?member=5939 BARNARD, Dr Toby.] British Academy. Retrieved 11 June 2015.</ref> His ''A New Anatomy of Ireland'' (2003) was notable for the depth of primary research that Barnard carried out to complete it. One reviewer commented that "This task of discovery and accumulation by itself is an heroic achievement."<ref>Alan Ford. [https://networks.h-net.org/node/16749/reviews/17874/ford-barnard-new-anatomy-ireland-irish-protestants-1649-1770 Review of Barnard, Toby, ''A New Anatomy of Ireland: the Irish Protestants, 1649-1770'']. H-Albion, H-Net Reviews. January, 2005. Retrieved 11 June 2015.</ref>  Barnard is a fellow of the [[British Academy]] and the [[Royal Historical Society]]. He did his undergraduate studies at [[The Queen's College, Oxford|The Queen's College]], Oxford, and was supervised for his PhD by [[Hugh Trevor-Roper]].

